snippet.textDisplay:
Kirby is a fundamental force of nature. He is a god of gluttony. Why do more than eat and sleep, if eating and sleeping are all that you desire? He need not hold malice in his heart because he cannot be harmed, and he knows that be it in 1 year or 1000 years, both friend and foe will die before him.
He destroys matter, but he does not destroy information. This is evident in his ability to emulate all that he consumes. The cosmic horrors that chase him are after this knowledge. This library of the universe that simply gathers dust in his mind. He is a collector of information, a protector of it. But with infinite power and infinite knowledge comes complacency. That is Kirby.

snippet.textDisplay: Perhaps Kirby is alchemy: the science of understanding, deconstructing, and reconstructing matter. However, it is not an all-powerful art. It is impossible to create something out of nothing. If one wishes to obtain something, something of equal value must be given. This is the law of equivalent exchange; the basis of all alchemy. In accordance to this law, there is a taboo among alchemists. Human transmutation is strictly forbidden. For what could equal the value of a human soul?

snippet.textDisplay: I think the nature metaphor works pretty well. Kirby is the blind idiot god personified; he is simple and uncaring, yet possesses power beyond mankind's reckoning, and if you threaten him he will hurt you. What is scariest about Kirby IS his simplicity, the idea that such power might be in the hands of what is little more than an animal, that there' might be no meaning to our intelligence or suffering except to consume and be consumed.

snippet.textDisplay:
I was a little disappointed that you didn’t discuss Dreamland, so I wanted to offer my take.

Kirby is a dreamer. A lot of his adventures happen in dreamland. Some of his enemies, while also being nightmarish, are literally referred to as nightmares iirc.

At least in the early games I’ve played (up to Super Star), we might not actually know much about the real, waking world Kirby. The projection we see in Dreamland is filled with childlike innocence and glee, despite the horrors he faces. He travels about via magical stars - what could be a more simple and evocative image of a childhood dream than soaring among the stars?

In Dreamland, he can be whatever he wants to be - his potential is limitless. Hence, the Copy ability. It’s less that he’s an eldritch abomination consuming everything in his path - rather, he views the world as brimming with potential, and is able to live out his fantasies and desires by assimilating things from the world around him. I’m sure some of you fantasized about being a sword master, a karate expert, a yo-yo wizard, having elemental powers etc as a child - in dreamland, Kirby can be all of that, and more, on a whim, without the intense effort and winnowing of potential life pathways we must accept as adults. This is to say nothing of some more telling abilities like those of Mirror Kirby - he damages his enemies by splitting himself in two, possibly hinting at body dysmorphia, or the fractured self that his dreaming and waking identities inhabit.

It’s also worth noting that, starting with Super Star, Kirby can create friends to join him on his adventure after copying abilities - one dimensional caricatures that are defined less by their personality, and more by their one cool skill or attribute. In my grade school experience, friendship was a currency that often hinged on trivialities like whether your “friend” had the coolest games or Magic the Gathering cards. In his naive innocence, Kirby sometimes Ling’s for a companion as he traverses the dreaming world, but can only conceive of them as a child does - essentially, as pet super heroes.

It may be worth considering that, in earlier games, including his debut title, Kirby doesn’t copy enemy abilities. Instead, he sucks them out and spits them out at others. He can also suck up blocks, stars, or use puffs of air to damage his foes. In essence, he’s reversing the harm being levied towards him and returning it unto his foes. Think of his iconic encounter with Whispy Woods, a sort of giving tree that produces an abundance of apples that could be used for nourishment - instead, they are corrupted into weapons that the fell treant used in an attempt to smite his foe. Kirby doesn’t slay the beast - he simply reverses the apples to the tree, albeit forcefully, thus reversing the harm that was originally directed towards him. He doesn’t kill or maim - he restores balance.

The same is true of the other bosses Kirby faces - he’s always simply reversing the harm they are doing, and by accomplishing this, he defeats them and restores order to the world. This is true of Dedede as well. I wonder if Dedede is meant to represent a playground bully? He’s done throughout the land, taking away everyone’s delicious food and candy, and hoarding it all for himself. He assaults Kirby not with guile, subterfuge or the arcane arts, but with sheer, raw, intimidating physical prowess. He’s almost brutish, despite his regal attire, wielding, of all things, a giant club. He is the tyrant of dreamworld, hoarding its riches and beating any dissenters into submission with all the grace and finesse of an irate gorilla.

If you’ve ever been bullied, I’m sure you’ve fantasized about taking your bully down a peg - maybe if you were generous, you’d seek to return all of the things he stole to the other children on the playground, just as Kirby restores food to Dreamworld as it spills out of Dedede’s castle, with his inflated self carrying it aloft, signaling that, in both a physical and metaphorical sense, Kirby has risen above his aggressor and become the bigger man. Yet he chooses to restore power to the people, rather than keeping it for himself. In at least one iteration of the fight (Super Star), it takes place in a boxing ring, with an audience cheering him on, perhaps referencing a public humiliation of the bully.

I’d like to keep going - we could talk about Meta Knight, a darker, more cynical reflection of Kirby, or enemies like Kracko, ominous, staring, spiked eyes that monitor Kirby’s every move, or the items that give him super powers, including magical candies... but I think you get my point. Kirby’s take represents all the simplicity, naïveté, and kind-hearted adventure in the dreams of a child. A world where you can be anything you want to be, where villains are simple and their harm on the world can be reversed, where everyone gets to share and get along once the bullies have been - not obliterated - just subverted.

Sounds kinda nice, huh?

snippet.textDisplay:
People are bringing up that Kirby has a pocket dimension in his body and while that’s not false , I want to say that’s not confirmed either.

I want to bring up a hypothesis that Kirby converts any matter he inhaled into “Star Energy” since that’s what we always see him spit out at his enemies. He will always produce “Star Energy” proportionate to the amount of matter he inhales. Everything Kirby inhales will inevitably return to the environment, even if he copies someone’s abilities he’ll eventually discard them.

The real question is what happens to the enemies he inhales? Most are usually under orders by leaders like Haltmann or Queen Sectonia or maybe they’re unfamiliar with Kirby, but other enemies have fought him repeatedly.

My theory is that minions don’t truly die when they’re inhaled by Kirby. Perhaps the process of being converted into Star Energy is an experience of bliss and enlightenment that’s incomprehensible to the player. That’s why we see so many enemies challenge Kirby again and again despite knowing they’ve no chance against him. their souls are completely cleansed of any malice or negative emotion. In this way, Kirby plays a vital part to Dreamland’s ecosystem or even to the universe.

And then, finally that same Waddle-Dee you inhaled in green-greens opens his eyes in his bedroom as if waking up from a refreshing nap...
